http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.ktvu.com/news/13417265/detail.html&cid=1116515252&ei=muxeRumXK4OUrgO0p8XXDQ Suspect Blames British For Spy's Death - News Story - KTVU San Francisco Make KTVU.com Your Homepage Sign up for E-News Andrei Lugovoi (left) and another Russian had met in London with Alexander Litvinenko on Nov. 1, the day Litvinenko said he became ill. Suspect Blames British For Spy's Death Litvinenko Died Of Poisoning By Rare Radioactive Isotope POSTED: 2:49 am PDT May 31, 2007 The Russian businessman whom Britain has named as a suspect in the killing of ex-KGB agent Alexander Litvinenko said Thursday that he has evidence of British special services' involvement in the poisoning death. "Even if (British special services) hadn't done it itself, it was done under its control or connivance," Andrei Lugovoi told a news conference. Asked if he had evidence for the allegation, he said "I have evidence" but did not elaborate. A British government security official, who demanded anonymity in exchange for discussing Lugovoi's claims because of the sensitivity of the case, said suggestions British intelligence had involvement in Litvinenko's death were spurious. Britain last week said it had enough evidence to charge Lugovoi, who also worked for the KGB and its main successor agency the FSB, in the November killing of Litvinenko. Litvinenko, who died of poisoning by the rare radioactive isotope polonium-210, had fled to Britain several years earlier after becoming a strong critic of the Kremlin and received British citizenship. Lugovoi and another Russian had met in London with Litvinenko on Nov. 1, the day Litvinenko said he became ill. Britain has requested Lugovoi's extradition, but Russia has refused, saying the constitution does not permit such extraditions. Lugovoi has repeatedly asserted he is not guilty in the matter. On Thursday, Lugovoi also claimed that Britain had tried to recruit him to provide intelligence. British special services "asked me to collect compromising information on President (Vladimir) Putin," Lugovoi said. Lugovoi said the attempted recruitment occurred during business trips to Britain in previous years. He did not give a precise date, but indicated the alleged approach occurred in late 2005 or early 2006. London's Foreign Office, responsible for the country's overseas secret intelligence service MI6, declined to comment on Lugovoi's claim. But another government official with knowledge of Lugovoi, who also demanded anonymity because of the sensitivity of the case, said the allegations were untrue. . All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed. Military Spouses Become Scam Targets The American Red Cross said a new identity-theft scam targets family members of deployed troops. SLIDESHOW: Cathedral Near Lake Merritt Taking Shape SLIDESHOW: Coit Tower's Hidden Wonders Father Says Lohan Hooked On Alcohol And OxyContin Paula Abdul Found Her Purpose on 'Idol' Mother Pleads No Content To Richmond Baby Abandonment Officials Plan Documentary On Bay Bridge Construction 'Guru Of Ganja' Convicted Of Marijuana Charges Again Resisting Arrest Charges Dropped Against Redwood City Bodybuilder Petaluma Dog Owner Arrested After Child Attacked Porter Raiders Jersey Number Change Too Expensive Giuliani Says California Not Just A Political ATM Georgia Traveler Causes Global TB Scare Man Sentenced To 40-To-Life For SF Slaying Obama: Tax Wealthy To Pay For Health Care Clinton Picks Up LA Mayor's Endorsement Romney Pledges Salary To Charity If Elected McCain Urges Approval Of Immigration Overhaul "Law And Order" Star Set To Shake Up Republican Race Four Defendants Convicted Of Murdering 17-Year-Old In 2003 Suspect Arrested In Oakland Police Officer Shooting Menlo Park Police Warn Of Suspected Prowling Predators Coroner Says Actress' Death Was A Homicide US Supreme Court Rejects 'Night Stalker' Appeal 70-Year-Old Injured In San Francisco