http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-0&fd=R&url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/business/chance-of-a-challenge-to-bushs-man/2007/05/31/1180205426731.html&cid=1116788973&ei=muxeRumXK4OUrgO0p8XXDQ Chance of a challenge to Bush's man - Business - Business - theage.com.au Welcome to The Age. Chance of a challenge to Bush's man Bob Zoellick: The world in his hands. US PRESIDENT George Bush's nominee as head of the World Bank, Bob Zoellick, is virtually certain to be ratified by the bank's board after June 15. But developing nations could nominate a candidate as a protest against the convention that gives the US the right to name the bank's head. President Bush said Mr Zoellick had a distinguished career in diplomacy and development economics. "He's a committed internationalist," he said. "He is deeply devoted to the mission of the World Bank. He wants to help struggling nations defeat poverty, to grow their economics and offer their people the hope of a better life." The World Bank board said it welcomed the nomination of Mr Zoellick, a former diplomat and economist, who has served as US deputy secretary of state, and former special trade representative in the Bush Administration. But it reiterated its stance that nominations were open until June 15 and board meetings would be held to consider all nominations. This leaves open the possibility of a repeat of events at the International Monetary Fund in 2004 when a group of developing nations put forward another candidate against the European nominee, Rodrigo de Rato. The move would be little more than a protest because Germany, which led the charge for the removal of the former president Paul Wolfowitz, is believed to have indicated that Mr Zoellick would be acceptable. In Canberra, Treasurer Peter Costello said Mr Zoellick would be "an excellent candidate". The French Foreign Minister, Bernard Kouchner, also backed the appointment. "Mr Zoellick is certainly the right man for the job," he said. But he said Mr Zoellick would need to regain the trust of the international community following the Wolfowitz scandal. The World Bank has been paralysed by controversy over Mr Wolfowitz's handling of a pay package for his girlfriend. But long before that, Mr Wolfowitz was seen as a controversial character, particularly by the European representatives on the bank because of his role in driving the Iraq war policies of the Bush Administration. Even this week, Mr Bush was still backing Mr Wolfowitz, describing him as "an able public servant" and "a man of character and integrity". But in the bank, Mr Wolfowitz proved a divisive figure &#151; he had strong views about fighting corruption by suspending loans to countries without transparent banking systems &#151; and morale among the 10,000 staff is said to be low. Mr Zoellick promised to tackle that issue: "We need to put yesterday's discord behind us and to focus on the future together," he said. Although Mr Zeollick is also a Bush Administration insider, he also enjoys a strong reputation as a capable and intelligent diplomat. He was instrumental as US trade representative in establishing the Doha Round of trade talks, and has been a strong advocate of free trade agreements, including the US-Australia agreement. Mr Zoellick has also been involved in diplomatic efforts in the Darfur region of Africa and other initiatives to fight poverty, something President Bush was keen to highlight. "Bob has had a strong voice for Africa," he said. "He wants to help struggling nations defeat poverty to grow their economies and offer their people the hope of better life." But not all are flattering about Mr Zoellick, with his critics pointing to some personal failings, particularly a propensity to tirades and a strong view on almost everything. Mr Zoellick's penchant to lecture, point by point, with little concern for editorial compression, is said to have irritated his boss, Condoleezza Rice, in the State Department, even though she had a huge regard for his intellect. When you see news happening: SMS/MMS: 0406 THE AGE (0406 843 243), or us. Subscribe to The Age for your chance to win 12 years of Penfolds Grange! Chance of a challenge to Bush's man Bob Zoellick: The world in his hands. Place a classified ad Copyright &#169; 2007. The Age Company Ltd. Browse for a Date Telstra slams 'lapdog' watchdog Drought drains Graincorp profit Packer goes to Vegas Resources, banks boost market Trade figures point to strong domestic economy Cemex extends Rinker takeover offer Flexible labour keeping inflation at bay: Treasury Investa board backs takeover Stocks take a positive lead from Wall St No news on 'approaches' says Austar Loren lands in Oz Fans greet movie legend with flowers as she arrives for a film festival. Britney's ex to fund own second album and star opposite Keanu Reeves. Who gave Lohan alcohol? Officials ponder whether Lindsay Lohan, who is underage, was served alcohol in LA bars. Lock up the crackberry? Unique (and extreme) ways to get away from work for the hols. ALL MEN ARE LIARS Is this the only way to give up smoking? Weapons of seduction - II SAM AND THE CITY TV How far would you go to get laid? Sleepless world record attempt amusingly goes wrong. In the race for ever-thinner displays for TVs, mobile phones and other gadgets, Sony may have developed one to beat them all. Bloom sails into new seas Full Executive Style coverage Remember the time when science fiction writers and futurists were talking about permanent... News Store Alert will keep you informed. Get free news emails from theage.com.au.
