and Qatar abstained from voting in the resolution that was adopted by 10 votes to zero. Lebanon must now ratify the proposal by June 10, failing which the Security Council may independently authorize a tribunal, as it did in the case Rwanda and the former Yugoslavia. Hariri and 22 others were killed in a massive car bomb in the capital, Beirut, on February 14, 2005. A UN investigation into the killing implicated Syria and Lebanese security forces in the attack, although Damascus strongly denied any involvement. Four pro-Syrian Lebanese generals accused in the murder have been under arrest for more than a year. Lebanese Prime Minister Fouad Siniora welcomed the Security Council resolution saying the ratification of the international tribunal is a victory for Lebanon, and for all the Lebanese. Rafik Hariri's son Saad Hariri, said the tribunal was a turning point for the country and "an opportunity for all Lebanese to unite". Syria reiterated its stance that the special court violated "Lebanese sovereignty" and could plunge Lebanon into further instability. Syrian President Bashar Assad has said any Syrial would not deport any Syrian suspects and they would be tried in Syria. Copyright &copy; 2007 RealTimeTraders.com, Inc. All rights reserved. By using this site, you agree to the Terms of Service How To Use RTTNews.com
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/14i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.alalam.ir/english/en-NewsPage.asp%3Fnewsid%3D041030120070531101426&cid=1116836088&ei=muxeRumXK4OUrgO0p8XXDQ Thursday, 31 May 2007 Three US Soldiers Killed in Iraq BAGHDAD, May 31--Three US soldiers have died in a pair of incidents which the US military reported late Wednesday, cementing May's position as the deadliest month of the war since 2004. Two soldiers were killed by a roadside bomb during a foot patrol Wednesday, the military said without specifying the exact location. Another soldier died from a "non-battle related cause" in Baghdad Tuesday, bringing the total for May to 116, the highest since 137 troops died in the November 2004 full scale invasion of Fallujah. Speaking of May, Brig. Gen. Perry Wiggins, deputy director of regional operations with the US Joint Chiefs of Staff, told reporters at a Pentagon briefing, "First and foremost, it's been a tough month." Wiggins attributed the rise in casualties to an ongoing security crackdown, explaining that four years into the occupation, "we're moving into places where we haven't been, not necessarily before." The latest fatalities bring the number of US soldiers killed in Iraq since the March 2003 invasion to 3,468, according to an AFP count based on Pentagon figures. On Thursday, the US military said five Americans and two other soldiers died when a Chinook helicopter was apparently shot down in Afghanistan's Helmand province. Democrats in control of the US Congress have been pressing Bush to agree to a timetable for pulling troops from Iraq, an idea firmly opposed by the president. The White House said Wednesday Bush would like to see a lengthy US troop presence in Iraq like the one in South Korea. Senate Democratic Leader Harry Reid immediately shot back, saying it is time for Bush to "recognize the reality on the ground in Iraq" that US troops are mired in Iraq and a change in course is urgently needed. "Democrats know that Americans demand realistic plans, not more White House rhetoric, rosy predictions and best-case scenarios," Reid said. Meanwhile, South Korea denied reports that it was leaning towards the extension of the stationing of its troops in Iraq. On Wednesday, a US television news claimed that South Korea has decided to extend the stay of the troops by another year while reducing the size of the contingent to 800 or 900. But South Korean Defense Minister said "there is no change in our position to submit a plan on terminating the mission of troops to parliament by the end of June". The latest fatalities bring the number of US soldiers killed in Iraq since the March 2003 invasion to 3,468. Make Alalam your homepage Copyright © 2004 - 2007 Alalam Inc.
