http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/19-1&fd=R&url=http://denver.bizjournals.com/denver/stories/2007/05/28/daily21.html%3Fjst%3Db_ln_hl&cid=1116798859&ei=muxeRumXK4OUrgO0p8XXDQ ACLU sues Jeppesen over CIA flights - The Denver Business Journal: for free extra services. News From Other Cities Subscribe to Print Edition Advertise in Print Edition Subscribe to Print Edition Subscribe to the Print Edition People in the News Travel - Airlines & Airports View Denver Jobs - 1270 jobs today How big a factor is it? ACLU sues Jeppesen over CIA flights The Denver Business Journal - 2:45 PM MDT Wednesday, May 30, 2007 American Civil Liberties Union filed a federal lawsuit Wednesday against Jeppesen DataPlan Inc. of San Jose, Calif., on behalf of alleged victims of U.S. government torture. Jeppesen DataPlan is part of aviation-data provider of Colorado. Based in Englewood, Jeppesen Sanderson is a subsidiary of aircraft manufacturer The ACLU alleges in its suit, filed in Northern California federal court, that Jeppesen knowingly provided flight services to the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) , which enabled the secret transport of three terrorism suspects to overseas locations for interrogation and torture. The terrorism suspects are Binyam Mohamed of Ethiopia, Italian citizen Abou Elkassim Britel and Ahmed Agiza of Egypt. The suit contends Jeppesen -- through its international trip and flight-planning operation in San Jose -- "has been a main provider of flight and logistical support services for aircraft used by the CIA ...," according to an ACLU statement. Mike Pound, a Jeppesen Sanderson spokesman, was unavailable for comment this afternoon. But earlier today, Pound told CBS News that Jeppesen officials had no comment about the suit because they hadn't seen it yet. Pound did tell the television network that Jeppesen doesn't know the purpose of customers' flights. "We create flight plans, what the fuel requirements might be, where they might refuel, the airports they might use ... It's not our practice to ever inquire about the purpose of a trip," Pound told CBS. Anthony Romero, the ACLU's executive director, chastised American companies that allegedly profit from the U.S. government's so-called "extraordinary rendition" program, which allows the CIA to transport terrorism suspects outside this country. "Corporations that choose to participate in such activity can and should be held legally accountable," Romero said in a statement. Further allegations in the suit include: Mohamed was flown to Morocco in 2002 where he was interrogated and tortured for 18 months. He later was taken to Kabul, Afghanistan, and Guantanamo Bay, Cuba, where he remains. Britel was flown from Pakistan to Morocco and tortured there. He's still in Morocco. Agiza was flown from Sweden to Egypt, where he was tortured and otherwise abused. He remains in Egypt. The ACLU filed suit under this country's Alien Tort Statue, which allows aliens to bring legal claims in the United States. Jeppesen Sanderson employs 3,000 people around the world -- 1,250 of them in Colorado. The company serves 85 percent of the world's airlines with navigational data, flight planning and operations solutions. Subscribe or renew online Alaska Airlines to serve Hawaii Cargo center opens in South Boston Reports: Russian airline orders 15 Dreamliners ACLU sues Jeppesen over CIA flights American to launch MSP-LaGuardia service [Minneapolis / St. Paul] Business tax credit for private school donations faces court challenge Business, political leaders unite over immigration debate Supreme Court declines to hear challenge of school vouchers Ryanair signs $1.9B Boeing order Boeing sells 787s to Russian airline Qatar picks Airbus over Dreamliners Pinellas airport takes noise abatement steps New approach and fewer planes means less noise for airport Goodrich inks supply contract Jeppesen reaches for the sky with downtown San Jose lease Boeing completes $1.5 billion acquisition Today's Latest News 