http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13-2&fd=R&url=http://www.dailyherald.com/story.asp%3Fid%3D318063&cid=1116775557&ei=muxeRumXK4OUrgO0p8XXDQ Daily Herald | News Subscribe to the Daily Herald Lake in the Hills Thursday, May 31, 2007 7 DAY STORY SEARCH Scalia's daughter admits to DUI DAILY HERALD LEGAL AFFAIRS WRITER Posted Wednesday, May 30, 2007 The daughter of U.S. Supreme Court Justice Antonin Scalia admitted Wednesday driving drunk in Wheaton. Ann S. Banaszewski, 45, pleaded guilty to misdemeanor DUI after her arrest earlier this year outside a fast-food restaurant. Banaszewski was placed on 18 months of court supervision and ordered to perform 140 hours of public service, nearly one-third of which must be with an agency that serves children. She also must continue with counseling and treatment and attend a victim-impact panel regarding the effects of drunken driving. Banaszewski was fined $2,155. Police stopped her Ford Ecoline van at 7:25 p.m. Feb. 12 near Gamon Road and Longfellow Drive after a motorist alerted them to a possible intoxicated driver. Her blood-alcohol level is unknown because she declined to submit to a Breathalyzer test. Prosecutor Michael O'Donnell said she failed a field-sobriety assessment and admitted drinking a half bottle of vodka earlier that evening. In exchange for the plea, prosecutors agreed to drop child endangerment allegations. Banaszewski, a mother of five, had three of the children in her van that night. After the arrest, she voluntarily checked herself into a two-month in-patient treatment program followed by another week in a hospital. She also is attending Alcoholics Anonymous meetings. "We're very satisfied with the outcome of this case," defense attorney Donald Ramsell said. "I believe we were able to show the prosecution she's a very fine mother and is addressing whatever concerns were needed." DuPage Associate Judge Daniel Guerin presided over the plea deal. He granted Banaszewski a judicial driving permit Wednesday allowing her to drive only to counseling and treatment sessions. The judge, though, ordered her to abstain from alcohol, and prohibited her from driving with her children until she regains full driving privileges in late September. Banaszewski had an otherwise spotless criminal and driving history. She declined to comment Wednesday while leaving court. E-mail story to friend Med Admission Coordinator Perform hospital-based patient adm... DELIVERY - Newspaper *Great 2nd Income* USA Today is lookin... INSTALLER/Wall Fabric Must speak English, have car, be relia... BARBER * Lake Zurich area. Mostly appointments. Full time. ... DRIVERS SIGN ON BONUS - $500 6 drivers needed for Woodridge ... View All Top Jobs Pingree Grove's Wester selling his shop On the trail of TB case Aurora man helps catch murder suspect A lot of talk, but no change for Cubs Twins’ sweep leaves Guillen at a loss Bryant backs off on seeking trade Ex-Flyers still aren’t big Fans Sox reunite with Thomas tonight Two paths cross again Northwest Airlines exits bankruptcy protection Motorola to trim another 4,000 jobs iTunes debuts songs free of DRM  Three companies settle shareholder lawsuits , Paddock Publications, Inc. |
