http://www.mercurynews.com/news/ci_6026687&cid San Jose Mercury News - ACLU targets planner of so-called CIA torture flights san jose / valley start / stop paper (From the last 24 hours) ACLU targets planner of so-called CIA torture flights Prosecutors: Aptos woman lived high life on &#36;1.5 million stolen... Kawakami: Bryant reveals a tortured soul Spector defense targets forensic errors Rivals Steve Jobs, Bill Gates talk like old pals ACLU targets planner of so-called CIA torture flights SUIT ALLEGES FIRM ORGANIZED FLIGHTS Article Launched: 05/31/2007 01:33:53 AM PDT Mohamed vs. Jeppesen Dataplan Inc. court complaint (PDF) The American Civil Liberties Union on Wednesday charged that a company with offices in downtown San Jose helped the CIA transport three men who were blindfolded, housed in small quarters, beaten until their bones broke and left with mutilated genitals during brutal interrogations. Using flight documents obtained in Europe, the ACLU filed suit against the company, Jeppesen Dataplan Inc., in the U.S. District Court for Northern California for its part in the alleged kidnapping, torture and inhumane treatment of the three. From an office on Santa Clara Street in downtown San Jose, Jeppesen employees take calls from customers planning international flights or looking for weather reports. According to the complaint, Jeppesen helped the CIA get fly-over and landing permits in other countries and provided itineraries and lodging for the flight crews. The flights took people the CIA wanted to interrogate to prisons in countries - Morocco and Egypt - that allow torture or to then-secret CIA-run detention facilities where the U.S. government argues that its own laws do not apply, according to the lawsuit. "These are places the whole world, including our own State Department, know use torture as an interrogation procedure," ACLU attorney Ann Brick said. According to the lawsuit, the company worked with at least 15 of the CIA planes for a total of 70 flights. Jeppesen spokesman Mike Pound said he could not comment on the lawsuit nor could he confirm whether or not Jeppesen scheduled flights for the CIA. "We've got thousands of customers. Every one of them has the expectation of privacy," Pound said. The company, he added, works with private pilots, companies with planes and, on occasion, governments. But during a press conference outside the company's downtown office, the ACLU's Brick alleged "this company provided essential flight information and material support that allowed the CIA" to carry out its interrogation program. CIA suit thrown out A similar lawsuit brought by the ACLU against the CIA for another case has been twice thrown out by U.S. courts after the government said it could not release key information in the case because doing so could harm national security. The ACLU also announced Wednesday that it will petition the U.S. Supreme Court to hear that case on the grounds of a 1789 law that allows foreign nationals to bring cases in U.S. courts, the same law it is using in the Jeppesen case. The men in Wednesday's lawsuit are Ahmed Agiza, 45, an Egyptian citizen living in Sweden; Abou Elkassim Britel, 40, of Italy; and Binyam Mohamed, an Ethiopian seeking political asylum in England. Agiza was in the process of applying for political asylum in Sweden with his family when he was picked up by Swedish security police and handed over to the CIA in 2001, according to the ACLU. The group reports that CIA officers stripped him, blindfolded him, inserted suppositories in him and put him aboard a Jeppesen-arranged plane on a flight to Egypt, where he was wanted for allegedly being part of an outlawed political group. He remains in prison in Egypt, a country known to use torture on its inmates. Police in Pakistan picked up Mohamed as he traveled back to England from Afghanistan in 2002. Blindfolded and shackled, he was allegedly put on a Jeppesen-arranged flight to Morocco. There he was imprisoned and guards cut his genitals and beat him as they questioned him about Al-Qaida, according to the ACLU. Fearing more torture, the ACLU says Mohamed repeated what his captors wanted to hear in a canned confession. In 2004 he was put on another Jeppesen-coordinated flight and sent to Guanta&#96;namo Bay, where he is still imprisoned. As Britel visited Iran and Pakistan on a research trip in 2001, he was picked up by Pakistani police in Lahore and beaten and turned over to the CIA, the ACLU alleges. The CIA placed Britel onto a plane arranged by Jeppesen, the group says, and took him to a Moroccan prison, where he was beaten and deprived of food and sleep. Under stress, he eventually signed a confession that the ACLU says he was never allowed to read. He was sentenced to nine years in prison. Contact Leslie Griffy at lgriffy@mercurynews.com or (408) 920-5945. The Mercury News is pleased to let readers post comments about an article at the end of the article. Please increase the credibility of your post by including your full name and city when commenting. Commission delays San Jose Flea Market vote De Anza protest planned Edwards woos voters at Google ACLU targets planner of so-called CIA torture flights Giuliani works Peninsula crowd Hazardous waste plant must close Book details UCSC's hidden treasures Copyright 2007 San Jose Mercury News Privacy Policy and Terms of Use MNG Corporate Site Map
