http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/10-2&fd=R&url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news%3Fpid%3D20601103%26sid%3DaEa6B2FlitHM%26refer%3Dus&cid=1116801824&ei=muxeRumXK4OUrgO0p8XXDQ , May 31 12:16 , May 31 17:16 , Jun 01 01:16 Australia & New Zealand Bush to Propose Plan for Post-2012 Greenhouse Gas Reductions May 31 (Bloomberg) -- President George W. Bush will propose today a new round of discussions aimed at setting long-term goals by the world&#39;s largest energy users to reduce greenhouse gas emissions. The president, in a speech today, will announce plans to convene a group of the largest emitters and energy users, including China and India, with the aim of reducing greenhouse gas emissions, blamed for global warming. ``Within the next 18 months we&#39;d like to see if we can achieve consensus on a long-term goal for reducing greenhouse gas emissions,&#39;&#39; a senior administration official said. The president&#39;s proposal comes as he prepares to meet with the leaders of the Group of Eight next week. U.S. negotiators have sought to eliminate climate-change targets from declarations being prepared for the meeting. The U.S. currently has a target of reducing its greenhouse gas intensity, a measure of emissions per unit of economic growth, by 18 percent by 2012. The president in 2001 withdrew the U.S. from the Kyoto Protocol, a multinational agreement that called for 35 nations to reduce emissions 5.2 percent below 1990 levels by 2012. ``The president will propose to help lead the discussions on a post-Kyoto framework,&#39;&#39; the official said. Europeans have called for long-term greenhouse gas emission reductions of 50 percent below 1990 levels by 2050. Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe last week called for 50 percent emission reductions, without setting a baseline. To contact the reporter on this story: Tina Seeley in Washington at Last Updated: May 31, 2007 10:01 EDT Wachovia to Buy A.G. Edwards for $6.8 Billion, Doubling Brokerage Division Economy 