You need to send signals that say, â€˜Iâ€™m here and Iâ€™m going to win.â€™â€ Even though advisers have said Mr. Thompson is likely to enter the race in July, reports that he might have to compete in the Aug. 11 Ames, Iowa, straw poll, an important early gauge of support in the first caucus state. Senator Barack Obama and Mitt Romney outline their foreign policy proposals in the July/August issue of Foreign Affairs magazine. The Washington Postâ€™s reports that while the candidates differ on issues like Iraq and climate change, both â€œare at pains to move beyond Iraq toward an overarching vision that will convince an unsettled and war-focused public that this, too, shall pass.â€ Mr. Romney, who as governor of Massachusetts enacted a plan to require all citizens to have health insurance, called on Republicans to tackle the issue during an appearance in Iowa. &#8220;I know the Democrats are talking about that. There&#8217;s no question it&#8217;s going to be pushed by them,&#8221; he said, as reported in The . &#8220;The Republicans have to talk about it as well.&#8221; Mr. Obama called on Senator Christopher J. Dodd, a rival who heads the Senate Banking Committee, to hold hearings on executive pay. Senator John McCain, whose support of the current immigration compromise has been derided by some of his Republican competition, seemed more like he was talking to critics during an Fox News Channel&#8217;s &#8220;The O&#8217;Reilly Factor&#8221; last night than to the host, Bill O&#8217;Reilly. &#8220;Right now it&#8217;s de facto amnesty because we have 12 million people here illegally. It is a national security issue,&#8221; he said. &#8220;You&#8217;ve got two choices here, Bill. You either round up and deport 12 million people and I know of no one who thinks that&#8217;s a good idea or practicable. Or you make sure that you do everything possible to make sure that they pay a very heavy price for having acted illegally and breaking our laws.&#8221; Senator Sam Brownback elaborates on his views about evolution in a today: &#8220;The truths of science and faith are complementary: they deal with very different questions, but they do not contradict each other because the spiritual order and the material order were created by the same God.&#8221; John Edwards plans to unveil his proposal for dealing with high gas prices today in Menlo Park, Calif. Gov. Bill Richardson and Mr. Dodd joined the top-tier Democrats in announcing they will not participate in a debate sponsored by the Congressional Black Caucus on Fox News Channel. The impact of the new primary schedule is palpable in Florida, reports The , noting the increase in candidate appearances there compared to previous campaign seasons. 4 comments so far... While fashions can change, bald guys are at a great disadvantage in this era of hairiness. It is true that Ike and Adlai were bald, but Ike was a political superhero even before running and Adlai&#8211;as talented as any candidate in the 20th Century, lost. After JFK hairified the entire era with his swept-brow woman-killer pate plumage, the world went nuts. The Beatles&#8217; came ashore with their mop tops; ever-longer men&#8217;s hair started racing to toward the floor. Even the rednecks started wearing mullets. Truman said Americans in 1948 would not vote for a man with a mustache, and so it was. Walrus mustaches used to be OK for leaders, but fashion had changed. Except for Sweet Baby James Taylor, the prominent go to extraordinary lengths to keep up their hair. Some of the candidates this year had their scalps treated like crop production fields with transplants set in even rows so that a later crop could yield fruit. See John Edwards. Chaney is bald&#8211;not a good sign for any bald guy. Voldemort is bald too, but that is less portentous than Chaney&#8217;s open sunroof. What makes Thompson think the public will choose him over a full head of hair?, He&#8217;s a man who walked between raindrops during his tenure in the Senate. Like James Buchanan, Thompson has no recent record of his views on the divisive issues of the day&#8211;especially those issues that divide Republicans. This would be clever posturing if he looked like Charlton Heston, but Thompson doesn&#8217;t look like a hairy Moses. He doesn&#8217;t even look like a fourth generation member of the old eastern establishment posing as a Texas hick. Thompson looks like Grandpa Munster or Elmer Fudd without the animation and speech impediment. Better for the Republicans to choose Sam Waterson, with his full head of hair, if their coalition needs a political non-entity to keep it from self-destructing. God forbid that the nation actually pick someone whose experience prepares him to govern and whose personality suggests leadership rather than clever, flexible pandering&#8211;you know, play-acting a part. Why is nobody with a mustache running? Oh yeah, Teddy Roosevelt&#8217;s daughter Alice put a hex on presidential mustaches&#8211;the &#8220;man on the wedding cake&#8221; joke. If only someone could come up with a good joke about actors who seek real world power. â€” Posted by IssyWise Mr. Brownback&#8217;s Op-Ed demonstrates yet again the religionist claim to authority that has no substantiation in reality to make certain things non-negotiable. It&#8217;s a shield for irrationality and unresponsiveness, constructed out of nothing. It is simply a fraudulent falsehood to assert that there is a &#8220;guiding intelligence&#8221; to the universe and you are privy to its intentions, as Brownback baldly claims. I see nothing in either Mr. Obama&#8217;s nor Mr. Romney&#8217;s foreign relations essays that suggests they have any awareness of the damage done to the international rule of law by Bush&#8217;s Iraq invasion on a trumped-up false pretext, and the need for the US to demonstrate to the world that we can contain our own war criminals as we maintain the world&#8217;s biggest arsenal. â€” Posted by Steve Bolger Fred said he wan